  The minimum (worst case) value of a long-only portfolio of bonds, over a
convex set of yield curves and spreads, can be estimated by its sensitivities
to the points on the yield curve. We show that sensitivity based estimates are
conservative, i.e., underestimate the worst case value, and that the exact
worst case value can be found by solving a tractable convex optimization
problem. We then show how to construct a long-only bond portfolio that includes
the worst case value in its objective or as a constraint, using convex-concave
saddle point optimization.
